  <entry>
    <title>The basic operation of numpy</title>
    <link href="http://yoursite.com/2018/09/30/The-basic-operation-of-numpy/"/>
    <id>http://yoursite.com/2018/09/30/The-basic-operation-of-numpy/</id>
    <published>2018-09-30T07:06:47.000Z</published>
    <updated>2018-09-30T07:13:32.069Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<link rel="stylesheet" class="aplayer-secondary-style-marker" href="\assets\css\APlayer.min.css"><script src="\assets\js\APlayer.min.js" class="aplayer-secondary-script-marker"></script><script class="meting-secondary-script-marker" src="\assets\js\Meting.min.js"></script><p>What is numpy?&nbsp;&nbsp;Here is the definition of numpy library in wikipedia:</p><blockquote><p>NumPy/ˈnʌmpaɪ/ is a library for Python, adding support for large, multi-dimensional arrays and matrices, along with a large collection of high-level mathematical functions to operate on these arrays.</p></blockquote><p>In a word, numpy can make it more convenient for us to operate array and matrix in Python, with high efficiency.</p><p><br></p><h3 id="Begin-to-use"><a href="#Begin-to-use" class="headerlink" title="Begin to use"></a>Begin to use</h3><p>Firstly, if you haven’t install this library please use <code>pip install numpy</code> to get it.</p><p>Typing <code>numpy</code> for many times is a waste, so we usually <code>import numpy as np</code></p><p><br></p><h3 id="Numpy-Array-amp-Matrix"><a href="#Numpy-Array-amp-Matrix" class="headerlink" title="Numpy Array &amp; Matrix"></a>Numpy Array &amp; Matrix</h3><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="comment"># create arrays</span></span><br><span class="line">arr1 = np.array([i <span class="keyword">for</span> i <span class="keyword">in</span> range(n)])</span><br><span class="line">arr2 = np.zeros(shape=(row_size, col_size), dtype=int)</span><br><span class="line">arr3 = np.ones(shape=(row, col))</span><br><span class="line">arr4 = np.full(shape=(row, col), fill_value=v)</span><br><span class="line">arr5 = np.arange(head, end, step_length)</span><br><span class="line">arr6 = np.linspace(head, end, divide_numbers)</span><br><span class="line">arr7 = np.random.randint(head, end)  <span class="comment"># Right open interval</span></span><br><span class="line">np.random.seed()  <span class="comment"># set the seed, if seed is equal then random nums are the same</span></span><br><span class="line">np.random.random(size=(<span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">5</span>))</span><br><span class="line">np.random.normal(mean_value, variance, size)  <span class="comment"># random distribution</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h4 id="propeties"><a href="#propeties" class="headerlink" title="propeties"></a>propeties</h4><ul><li>ndim</li><li>shape</li><li>size</li></ul><p>you can use slide operation to visit elements in an array, such as <code>arr[:2,:4,2]</code></p><h4 id="functions"><a href="#functions" class="headerlink" title="functions"></a>functions</h4><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">arr.reshape(row, col)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>[annotation]: if one of the params is determined, another can be set as -1 (means auto distribute)</p><h5 id="combination"><a href="#combination" class="headerlink" title="combination"></a>combination</h5><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">np.concatenate([arr1, arr2], axis=0/1)</span><br><span class="line">np.vstack()  pile vertically</span><br><span class="line">np.hstack()  pile horizontally</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h5 id="devide"><a href="#devide" class="headerlink" title="devide"></a>devide</h5><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">arr1, arr2 = np.split(arr, [n], &lt;axis=1&gt;)</span><br><span class="line">split arr (position is n)</span><br><span class="line">np.vsplit()</span><br><span class="line">np.hsplit()</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h4 id="Built-in-mathematical-operations"><a href="#Built-in-mathematical-operations" class="headerlink" title="Built-in mathematical operations"></a>Built-in mathematical operations</h4><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">np.sin(arr)</span><br><span class="line">np.exp(arr)</span><br><span class="line">np.abs(arr)</span><br><span class="line">np.log&lt;num&gt;(arr) <span class="comment">#log(arr) means napierian logarithm</span></span><br><span class="line">np.exp(<span class="number">3</span>, arr) <span class="comment">#means e^x</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>Arithmatics are aimming at each elements in the array/matrix</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">A*B: means every elements <span class="keyword">in</span> A multiply corresponding elements <span class="keyword">in</span> B</span><br><span class="line">A.dot(B)：means the normal multiplication <span class="keyword">for</span> matrics, A*B</span><br><span class="line">A.T： the transposition</span><br><span class="line">np.linalg.inv(arr)：inverse matrix of arr</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h4 id="Aggregation-operation"><a href="#Aggregation-operation" class="headerlink" title="Aggregation operation"></a>Aggregation operation</h4><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">np.sum(arr)</span><br><span class="line">np.max(arr)</span><br><span class="line">np.min(arr)</span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># also support for axis</span></span><br><span class="line">np.prod(arr): multiplication of all the elements</span><br><span class="line">np.mean(arr): mean value</span><br><span class="line">np.median(arr): median value</span><br><span class="line">np.precentile(arr, q=n): the value which position <span class="keyword">is</span> at n%</span><br><span class="line">np.var(): variance</span><br><span class="line">np.std(): standard diviation</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h5 id="Index"><a href="#Index" class="headerlink" title="Index:"></a>Index:</h5><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">np.argmin(arr): return the index of the mininum</span><br><span class="line">np.argmax(arr):</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h5 id="sort"><a href="#sort" class="headerlink" title="sort"></a>sort</h5><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">np.random.shuffle(arr)：make arr disordered</span><br><span class="line">np.sort(arr)：sort</span><br><span class="line">np.partion(arr, n): quicksort of arr</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>you can add <code>arg</code> tag before the method’s name (e.g. argpartition, argsort), in this way it will return the array/matrix consist of indexs nums</p><p>It alse support <code>axis</code> param</p><h5 id="fancy-indexing"><a href="#fancy-indexing" class="headerlink" title="fancy indexing:"></a>fancy indexing:</h5><p>using slice to select regular eles is enough, using fancy<br><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">ind = np.array([<span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">2</span>]</span><br><span class="line">               [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">3</span>])</span><br><span class="line">arr[ind]  <span class="comment"># return corresponding index</span></span><br><span class="line">row = np.array([<span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>])</span><br><span class="line">col = np.array([<span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>])</span><br><span class="line">arr[row, col]  <span class="comment">#return values of (0, 3),(1, 4),(2, 5)</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p><p>logic operations between arrays or matrices will return its bool type</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">np.sum(x &lt; <span class="number">3</span>)  <span class="comment"># x&lt;3 will return a bool matrix</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># this states means returning the nums of elems who &lt; 3</span></span><br><span class="line">np.count_nonzero</span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># literal meaning</span></span><br><span class="line">np.any(logical operation)  <span class="comment"># return true if any one is true</span></span><br><span class="line">ny.all(logical operation)  <span class="comment"># retunr true only when all is true</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h3 id="matplotlib-viusualization-tool"><a href="#matplotlib-viusualization-tool" class="headerlink" title="matplotlib (viusualization tool)"></a>matplotlib (viusualization tool)</h3><p><code>import matplotlib as mpl</code><br>always use its pyplot：<code>import matplotlib.pyplot as plt</code></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">plt.plot(x, y, color=<span class="string">""</span>, linestyle=<span class="string">"--"</span>, label=<span class="string">""</span>)</span><br><span class="line">plt.xlim(min, max)</span><br><span class="line">plt.axis([xmin,xmax,ymin,ymax])</span><br><span class="line">plt.xlabel(<span class="string">"xxx"</span>)</span><br><span class="line">plt.legend()  <span class="comment"># add represantation</span></span><br><span class="line">plt.title(<span class="string">""</span>)</span><br><span class="line">plt.show  <span class="comment"># call at alst to show the pic</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>scatter diagram:<br><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">plt.scatter(x, y, alpha=<span class="number">0.5</span>) <span class="comment">#alpha is the opaque degree</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>]]></content>
    
